<TEXT>
monsanto agricultural co of st louis mo 
has been given permission by the agriculture department to conduct 
the first field testing of a genetically altered soybean variety 
the new variety which contains a petunia gene is expected to 
be unaffected by glyphosate a weedkiller sold by monsanto under 
the trade name roundup testing begins this month and will continue 
through the summer at sites in jerseyville ill whiteville 
tenn and stuttgart ark 
glyphosate tolerance in soybeans would offer new production 
possibilities to american farmers james w glosser 
administrator of the departments animal and plant health 
inspection service said monday a single herbicide could be used 
without fear of damaging the crop rather than the mixtures and 
multiple applications now necessary 
glosser said the agency has evaluated the scientific data and 
methods to be used in the field tests and found them to be well 
designed and environmentally safe 
monsanto scientists engineered the new variety by transferring a 
petunia gene to soybeans greenhouse studies showed the new soybean 
to be tolerant of glyphosate and now scientists want to test it 
under field conditions 
the usda also has issued permits to a number of companies for 
field testing of some other genetically altered crops including 
cotton and tomatoes to see if they are resistant to weedkilling 
chemicals 
