nuclear regulatory commission the last regulatory maneuver in a 
prolonged campaign to block a lowpower license 
it would be arbitrary and capricious to issue the license 
in light of the great uncertainty that seabrook will ever 
receive an operating license wrote lawyers for massachusetts 
the town of hampton nh and the new england coalition on nuclear 
pollution 
the opponents cited seabrooks financial condition the lead 
owner has filed for bankruptcy protection coupled with geographic 
and demographic conditions around the plant that they say make it 
virtually impossible to provide adequate sheltering or reasonably 
prompt evacuations seabrook must have evacuation plans approved 
to receive a fullpower commercial license 
opponents argue that conducting lowpower tests could endanger 
workers and residents make decommissioning much more expensive and 
eliminate the chances of converting the 6 billion plant to another 
form of energy production 
even temporary operation at low power will result in 
irreversible plant contamination caused by radiation of the reactor 
and its component parts and the creation of highlevel radioactive 
waste the opponents said in the petition should a 
radiological accident occur at the seabrook plant it could cause 
irreversible health damage to the population around the plant 
if the nrc refuses the stay request the license will be issued 
immediately according to a march commission order that decision 
can come any time after friday the deadline for the plant owners 
to respond to mondays stay request 
but the opponents also asked the nrc to grant a oneweek 
