<TEXT>
a hungarian energy official tuesday was 
quoted as saying a controversial dam project opposed by tens of 
thousands of environmentalists could be stopped in the nations 
interest 
the statement was the latest sign hungary may pull out of the 
project a multimilliondollar plan with czechoslovakia and austria 
to make the danube river more navigable and build power stations in 
czechoslovakia and hungary 
about 140000 hungarians have signed a petition calling for a 
referendum on the project which has been under fire since it was 
first agreed to in the late 1970s 
opposition in hungary has become more vocal as democratic groups 
have gained more say in politics in recent months the more 
orthodox czechoslovak communists who insist the project should be 
completed expressed irritation with the opposition in their party 
daily last weekend 
the plan to build the hungarian dam at nagymaros about 30 miles 
upstream from budapest on the danube is seen by many hungarians as 
a symbol of the centralized economic planning of the past in which 
citizens were given no say 
czechoslovak officials already have invested 11 billion in a 
much larger dam and power station being built as part of the 
project at gabcikovo about 40 miles east of bratislava 
environmentalists have long argued the project affecting more 
than 60 miles of the danube will destroy wetlands with unique 
wildlife they also claim a huge underground reservoir of drinking 
water will be spoiled by the power stations and canals to be built 
along the river 
our position is that the nagymaros construction can be halted 
but gabcikovo must be completed istvan papp director of 
hungarys state energy economy institute told the daily mai nap 
newspaper on tuesday 
this compromise would be a solution best serving the nations 
interests he added 
experts on both sides acknowledge the projects are too 
interrelated for gabcikovo to be effective without the hungarian 
dam 
hungarys government and parliament are to debate the call for a 
referendum on nagymaros this month however even opponents of the 
project question the wisdom of putting such a complex issue to a 
popular vote 
papp said the government would save half a billion dollars by 
stopping investment in the project which on the hungarian side has 
been financed in part by austria in return for future deliveries of 
electricity 
papp said his calculations did not include the cost of 
compensating austria and czechoslovakia if hungary pulled out of 
the project 
</TEXT>
