<TEXT>
oregon farmers have planted 18 percent 
less acres of strawberries this year because of fluctuations in the 
migrant work force and complications of the new federal immigration 
law 
the harvest may cover even less acreage if more migrant pickers 
dont arrive in the next few weeks for the june picking 
this is the first full year officials can measure the effects of 
the immigration reform and control act of 1986 which penalizes 
growers who hire undocumented aliens traditionally the largest 
source of harvest workers employers face fines of 500 to 10000 
for each illegal worker and can be imprisoned after three 
violations 
while the numbers of both documented and undocumented workers 
are increasing as the june strawberry harvest nears far fewer 
pickers have arrived than last year when there was a surplus of 
about 30000 who were stranded without jobs food or housing 
two years ago a shortage of workers left 20 percent of the 
strawberry crop to rot in the fields many migrant workers 
mistakenly believed then that they would lose their chance for 
legal residency if they were caught in the united states last 
year word of the previous years shortage led to the surplus 
what happens this year may largely determine the future of 
oregons strawberry crop the nations second largest after 
california 
the oregon agricultural statistical service estimates 6400 
acres have been planted in strawberries down from 7800 acres the 
past two years 
many farmers last year just decided it was not worth it to 
grow strawberries knowing that the labor situation was uncertain 
said dalton hobbs spokesman for the oregon department of 
agriculture 
oregons smaller production shouldnt have a significant impact 
on the national strawberry crop however in california the number 
of acres planted in strawberries has increased 12 percent since 
1987 to an estimated 19000 acres this year 
danny santos manager of the migrant program for the governors 
commission on agricultural labor estimated oregon will need 40000 
workers to harvest this years crop 
santos said better wages and living conditions must be provided 
to attract a stable and legal labor force 
we as a state must learn how to become more competitive in 
getting workers he said 
oregon has teamed with washington and idaho to form a regional 
recruitment task force that works to secure an adequate labor 
supply the group is working with texas officials on an exchange 
program to make use of that states large farm labor pool and give 
those workers more work santos said 
other actions include financing child care health and education 
programs and providing grants to agencies that work to secure 
better housing 
if you provide services you not only get a skilled labor 
force but a stable labor force santos said 
growers who in the past have failed to provide adequate wages 
and housing will have a tough time getting their crops harvested 
said the rev david ziegler of st alexanders roman catholic 
church in cornelius about 20 miles west of portland 
growers talk about the immigration law but they have to 
accept responsibility for workers he said 
there are going to be a lot of growers who wont get their 
crops picked said ron taylor overseer at lloydene farms near 
cornelius 
one worker eloy aguirre of mexico said he still is waiting to 
be paid for his work last year at tankersley farms in washington 
county owner ron tankersley is serving a jail sentence for using 
illegal contractors this year aguirre will work for lloydene 
david beebe district director of the us immigration and 
naturalization service office in portland said the agency will 
focus on growers who hire illegal workers not on deporting those 
without documentation 
its the difference between working hard and working smart 
beebe said 
