<TEXT>
the national housing conference said tuesday 
that the nation faces the loss of hundreds of thousands of 
federally assisted housing units and urged a 10 billionayear 
program to preserve and produce housing for low and 
moderateincome families 
the conference a nonprofit organization of civic leaders and 
leaders of the housing industry said the inventory of federally 
assisted housing units is declining because of several factors and 
that no federal program is in place to replace lost housing 
john simon president of the group said at a news conference 
that the nation faces the imminent and longterm loss of between 
200000 and 12 million units of subsidized housing 
in calling for new federal spending he said congress and the 
administration have shown a willingness to spend massive amounts to 
bail out the savings and loan industry and provide agricultural 
subsidies and should do the same for affordable housing 
we think money can also be found and must be found to house 
our people he said 
if the loss in housing occurs simon said there would be 
massive displacement of poor and lowincome tenants and the 
working poor and a dramatic increase in the number of homeless 
families 
simon and other conference leaders said the problem is being 
created by the termination or expiration of federal subsidy 
contracts for housing projects the loss of assisted housing and 
public housing due to deterioration and inadequate maintenance and 
the prepayment of mortgages on privately owned subsidized housing 
the end of mortgages and subsidy contracts permit private owners 
of federally assisted housing to convert the housing to marketrate 
rental units or condominiums he said 
