the labor party battling to broaden its appeal 
after a decade in opposition on tuesday dumped its votelosing 
doctrine of unilateral nuclear disarmament 
urged on by party leader neil kinnock labors national 
executive voted 178 for a new policy of multilateralism under 
which a laborled government would scrap britains independent 
nuclear arsenal only in a negotiated arms control deal 
a 169 vote defeated a motion by the hardline left to set a 
deadline for scrapping britains submarinebased nuclear missiles 
unilaterally 
the national executive adopted an unopposed amendment whereby a 
labor government would negotiate nuclear disarmament with the 
soviet union if ussoviet negotiations stalled 
but the executive also adopted unopposed a resolution saying 
nuclear weapons are not a deterrent and of no practical use 
the governing conservative party contended this is tantamount to 
saying a labor government would never use nuclear arms 
labor leftwingers accused their party of betraying its 
principles and vowed to fight to reverse the new policy at the 
