<TEXT>
states directly affected by the extensive soil 
and groundwater pollution at federal nuclear weapons factories 
should be given a bigger role in shaping a longterm cleanup plan 
state officials told congress on tuesday 
health and environmental regulators from idaho south carolina 
colorado and washington state said the energy department which 
owns 16 major nuclear arms facilities in 12 states must show a 
clearer commitment to working with the states 
we should have been involved six months ago in the energy 
departments cleanup planning for the savannah river nuclear 
weapons site in south carolina said lewis shaw of the south 
carolina department of health and environmental control 
shaw said it was very difficult for his state to judge 
whether the energy departments proposed spending for cleanup is 
adequate in part because no one yet knows the full extent of soil 
and groundwater contamination at savannah river the site contains 
three active nuclear reactors and several processing plants 
there are almost certainly problems as yet undiscovered 
shaw told a special panel of house members from states that host 
or are adjacent to the nuclear facilities all of this suggests 
that currently projected cleanup costs may be short of what will 
actually be needed to properly restore the site in timely manner 
the bush administration has proposed spending 400 million on 
cleanup in the coming budget year 
estimates of the cost of cleaning up the energy department 
facilities over the next three decades range from about 80 billion 
to about 150 billion although energy secretary james d watkins 
said last week the cost could be far less 
watkins top advisor on the nuclear cleanup problem leo duffy 
told the house panel watkins opposes a house bill that would create 
a special commission to assess cleanup priorities and recommend 
ways of carrying them out 
we believe enactment of legislation at this time would prove 
counterproductive and would complicate efforts now underway 
within doe to address environmental concerns duffy said 
the bill passed the house energy and commerce committee last 
month 
last week the governors of 10 states sent watkins a letter 
expressing concern frustration and anger at the contamination 
and years of environmental neglect at the nuclear facilities which 
have been operating since the early 1950s 
the governors called for increased federal spending and a 
clarification of the role of the states in ensuring environmental 
compliance and overseeing the cleanup 
the state officials testifying tuesday complained that while the 
energy department in recent years had begun paying closer attention 
to the waste problem it still was unclear whether the department 
was committed to a longterm cleanup 
we are in a period of uncertainty in colorado as to how doe 
intends to assure that its annual budget requests are consistent 
with the time frames for cleanup said tim holeman an advisor on 
environmental issues to colorado gov roy romer 
holeman said his state thinks more federal money should be made 
available in the next budget year to assess and begin correcting 
waste problems at the rocky flats nuclear facility near denver 
which processes plutonium and makes weapons components 
terry husseman assistant director for waste management in the 
washington state department of ecology told the panel his state 
was satisfied with the 80 million that the bush administration 
planned to spend in the coming budget year to restore the 
environment at the hanford reservation weapons plant near richland 
wash 
we are however very concerned over future funding 
prospects husseman said he said washington gov booth gardner 
favors creating a federal trust fund to ensure that enough money is 
available to finish the cleanup at hanford and elsewhere 
