<TEXT>
a group of black employees is suing the 
pillsbury co accusing the food conglomerate of routinely engaging 
in race discrimination in hiring promoting compensating and 
disciplining black workers 
the complaint was filed monday in us district court in 
minneapolis on behalf of eight pillsbury employees and one person 
who applied for but failed to get a job with the company a judge 
will rule in about six months whether to certify the suit a class 
action representing present and former black employees 
paul sprenger the attorney representing the nine plaintiffs 
said their experiences at the company indicate widespread racist 
employment practices 
blacks are routinely put in the slow track as opposed to the 
fast track and reach the level beyond which they cant go and 
become frustrated sprenger said 
the complaint says one of the nine plaintiffs freida hodges of 
minneapolis applied for a job at pillsbury but was rejected 
because of her race the other eight all employees experienced 
discrimination in promotions unfair performance evaluations and 
harassment the suit says 
pillsbury which was acquired in january by grand metropolitan 
plc of london said monday that it has carefully reviewed the 
allegations in the complaint and concluded that they have no basis 
in fact 
most of the allegations involve alleged incidents which took 
place before grand metropolitan acquired pillsbury the company 
said pillsbury and grand met are strongly committed to the 
principle of equal employment opportunities for all employees and 
prospective employees 
sprenger said he began investigating the case two years ago he 
said that during that time he talked to the company in an effort to 
reach a settlement before filing a complaint but was unsuccessful 
part of the problem was getting a management decision because 
of the recent takeover he said 
sprenger is nationally known for his successful litigation in 
employment discrimination he has participated in many of the major 
classaction employment cases in minnesota rajender vs the 
university of minnesota national organization for women vs the 3m 
co and holden et al vs burlington northern 
it is an easy case to resolve if a serious commitment to 
future hiring and promotion practices can be addressed he said 
the complaint included a copy of a list of racist jokes that was 
freely circulated and condoned by pillsbury management 
employees sprenger said one of the plaintiffs diana sanders a 
secretary who was terminated in march in companywide layoffs 
obtained the list from upperlevel managers 
the complaint filed monday is the second class action 
racediscrimination complaint leveled at the company in 1974 a 
black woman charged race and sex discrimination after she was fired 
from her managementlevel job the case wound its way up to the 
eighth us circuit court of appeals before it was settled in 1984 
out of court 
sprenger said that because the settlement did not require 
pillsbury to change its employment and promotion practices it has 
perpetuated race discrimination 
</TEXT>
